P30L
Introduced in 2008, the P30L (for Long), has a slide and barrel that measure approximately a half-inch longer in length. Otherwise the P30L is essentially identical to the P30.

Like the P30, the P30L was designed as a modern police and security pistol and combines optimal function and safety. Ergonomic features include a special grip frame with interchangeable backstraps inserts and lateral plates, allowing the pistol to be individually adapted to any user.

Ambidextrous controls include dual slide releases, magazine release levers, and a serrated decocking button located on the rear of the frame (for applicable variants). A Picatinny rail molded into the front of the frame makes mounting lights, laser aimers, or other accessories easy and convenient. The extractor serves as a loaded chamber indicator providing a reminder of a loaded chamber that can be subtly seen and felt. The standard P30L is a 9 mm “Variant 3 (V3)” with a conventional double-action/single action trigger mode with a serrated decocking button on the rear of the slide.

P30LS models have the features of the “L” model with the addition of an ambidextrous safety lever mounted on both sides of the frame. LS models are available in conventional double-action/single action trigger mode with decocking button (“V3S” 9 mm and .40 S&W) and with HK’s enhanced double action only “V2” Law Enforcement Modification trigger. A special “V1” lightweight trigger pull model of the Law Enforcement Modification is also available.

Extensively tested, P30L and P30LS models have been adopted by several international police and security agencies. Excellent weight and balance make the P30L naturally pointable, easy to control, and accurate to shoot. An open notch rear sight with luminous (non-radioactive) contrast points allows for fast and accurate target acquisition, even under poor lighting conditions."

Daisy CO2 100 1962

The Model 100 was only produced in 1962. The trigger on this gun feels like a true single action semi-auto although it operates the elevator in addition to releasing the sear. Daisy reworked the gun and reintroduced it as the Daisy CO2 200 in 1963. The Daisy 100 holds 200 BBs in a hopper from which 5 BBs at a time are fed into a spring-loaded internal magazine.

The Chiappa Rhino barrel is aligned with the bottom most chamber which is the key component to Rhino's tame characteristics. The position of the barrel lowers the center of gravity and yields a centerline of the bore more in line with the shooter's arm allowing for the most natural ""point ability"" while engaging a target. This characteristic also drastically reduces both recoil and muzzle flip which insures subsequent shots to be on target faster. The reduction of the recoil allows for the use of ultra light alloys to be used in the construction of the Rhino minimizing any adverse effect. The flat sided cylinder design of the Rhino reduces the typical revolver profile allowing greater concealment.

Also included are a Target Sports Red/Green dot sight with integrated laser, 3 speedloaders (including a Safariland push button loader), and a Safariland Loading Block that sets up 14 (6 rnd) loads for the speedloader (a nice to have at the range!).  Original Box and owner’s manual also included.

751,http://www.armslist.com/posts/1928751,"For Sale:  A USED HECKLER & KOCH HK P7M13 9mm -- Squeeze-Cocker...CHANTILLY, Mfd 1988.","MO, Missouri, United States",$ 870,"Listed On: Saturday, July 27, 2013",Handguns,Heckler & Koch                                                                                ,9mm Luger (9x19)                                                                                ,no type,Pistol,"Probably one of the best all time pistol designs, this is a Heckler & Koch HK P7M13. Also known as a ""squeeze cocker"", this pistol is unique in the handgun world due to the ingenious feature built into the front grip strap. The front strap is actually a lever which performs several functions. First and foremost, by squeezing the lever, the gun is made ready to fire (hence the nickname). This action partially cocks the firing mechanism and the final trigger pull is light, crisp and consistant. To make the gun safe, all you have to do is relax your grip slightly and the lever pops back out decocking the firing mechanism. After the final shot is fired from the magazine the slide locks open and upon replacing a loaded mag, another squeeze of the lever instantly drops the slide, loads the chamber, cocks the firing mechanism so that you're immediately ready to shoot. The magazine release is ambidextrous. The pistol operates by a gas delayed blow-back system that allows the barrel to be fixed to the frame...this greatly improves accuracy. This pistol is in excellent shape with only very light wear. I'd grade the original finish about 97-98% with just a slight amount of finish wear to the right side at the edge of the muzzle and along the right edge of the back strap. There is some minor ""in-out"" wear on the edges of the magazine body. There is no rust or any pitting. The mechanics are in perfect working order and the bore is mirror bright. Looking at the internal components, it appears that this pistol is likely unfired!! It comes with one factory 13-round magazine. The ""II"" date code on the frame (and magazine) indicates this pistol was manufactured in 1988. It is also a ""Chantilly"" marked pistol which many HK collectors feel were of the highest quality. Instantly ready, instantly safe...the P7M13 was discontinued in 1994, but remains one of my all-time favorite handgun designs."

The PF-9 has a single stack magazine holding 7 rounds. It is one of the lightest and flattest 9 mm ever made. Firing mechanism is Double-Action Only with an automatic hammer block safety. The PF-9 is available in blued, parkerized, and hard chrome finishes. Grips are in black, grey, and olive drab.

The PF-9 retains the best features from our P-11 and P-3AT pistols combined into the flattest and lightest single stack 9mm configuration ever made. The barrel, locking system, slide stop, assembly pin, front sight, recoil springs and guide rod are adapted from the P-11. The PF-9 is nearly identical to the P-11 in length and height and shares the same exterior controls. The rear sight is a new design and is adjustable for windage with the supplied allen wrench as well as for elevation with the use of shims (not included). The included 7 round rectangular magazine is supplied with a finger extension base plate and numbered holes. The under barrel accessory rail shares the dimensions of the MIL-STD-1913 picatinny rail although there is only one locking notch in the forward position.
